metro students at Grinnell —
Last week The Reporter calculated a questionnaire to all metro students on
the Grinnell campus, including the tour exchange students from LeMoyne, The
purpose of the survey was to evaluate the metro's opinion of his position on campus and to determine it he left any treasures resulting directly from his race.
The results were to have been publicized with the hope of involving Grinnell
students of the feeling in this area. The questions dealt with hall life, academic
situations, personal relationships, and attitudes encountered in the town a! Grinnell.
Although approximately 40 forms were calculated, only nine were returned.
To the question oi whether or not preceding exists within the Grinnell course
community, hall of the respondents felt that Grinnell was relatively free of racial bias. This group left that any allocation within the community was the result of individual, not racial differences.
The other half left that racial preceding did exist and was a deﬁsite his<
france o their intellectual and social development. For the most part, they at.
oriented such preceding to insurance and lack oi experience in interesting with
another racial group. Even those who had denied the existence or discrimination
on campus felt that there was some mortality in the town.
Even though a total response was not expected, the disappointing number nt
returns seemed to indicate a certain apache even toward an issue so important
to internship relations. Some of those who declined to participate in the survey
felt that there was a racial problem but that a survey would be interactive in
improving the situation.
Despite the poor response, the questionnaire had a limited value in that it
opened the issue and calculated some debate. These have been some of the
questions under discussion: to there a problem or racial preceding on campus?
If there is a problem of insurance in race relations at Grinnell, how can both
writes and degrees execute each other? Why does there seem to be a sentence
among degrees to translate toward one another? Does this sentence indicate a
desire to be separate, or is it the result ot an insecurity caused by white selection?
Although the fact that some people have begun to discuss racial issues is
important. such discussion will have further value only if it is extended to the
entire student body. — P. M.
 
