Soccer a variety sport?
By Barry Anemia
Our variety teams are having
a poor year, but the Grinnell
Soccer Club has been quite successfuL There have been requests to recognize soccer as
a variety sport once again (it
was dropped two years ago with
the departure of its coach, living
Simone), and such an action
would seem to be a good idea.
Soccer cannon do anything but
become more important as a
college sport. The advert oi
American soccer leather will
certainly draw attention to this
sport played almost everywhere
else in the world, and the in—
create in high school soccer
that is due to follow will pm
side ready talent for the 00L
pages.
Organizing soccer as a variety
team would bring about several
benefits. The team would be as
speed unilorms, equipment, a
schedule of games, transportation, meals after away games,
variety letters, and coaching.
Grinnell, with its number of foreign students and students team
the east coast, who are more
likely to play soccer than their
midwestern schoolmates, seems
to have a jump on other area
conference schools in establishing a strong team. Coaching
would bring out the best in the
experienced men and add to the
squad talented students who
have never played,
little feels are
Disadvantages accruing from
variety status are also important. Two or the best players on
the club team are high school
exchange students; they, and
future high school students,
could not, of course, play on
the team. Also incredible would
be the hall-dozen freshmen on
the squad. The most important
Change would be the discipline.
Presently, the team has three
practices a week, informally
coaches by junior Richard
carl, ll‘Om Austria. Attendance
at games is voluntary, and
schedules are almost non—existing; games planned two weeks
in advance are considered fragrance objectives. With variety
status, this would all change.
Practices would be live times a
weeks, and mandatory. Games
would be scheduled far in advance, and players would he
expected to attend all away
games. Members of the club
with other campus commitments
might not be able to join the
team, due to either time involved, or the away games. The
fact that there is now no prev.
sure to play attempts many en—
thusiasts who would not so
preciatethe pressure ac<
completing a variety sport.
It would seem that in the
long run, making soccer a variety sport would be geneﬁdial,
both to the players and to the
college as a whole This opinion is shared by Mr. harley, the
Golf team almost
beolslovvo store
